==English==

===Etymology===
From Chaucer's character '''[[w:Pandarus|Pandare]]''' (in ''[[w:Troilus and Criseyde|Troilus and Criseyde]]''), from Italian '''[[w:Pandarus|Pandaro]]''' (found in [[w:BoccaccioBoccaccio]]), from Latin '''[[w:Pandarus|Pandarus]]''', from Greek '''[[Πάνδαρος]]'''. (See also Shakespeare's [[wikibooks:Troilus and Cressida|Troilus and Cressida]])

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈpændə/}} (''UK'')
*{{audio|en-us-pander.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A person who furthers the [[illicit]] love-affairs of others; a [[pimp]] or [[procurer]], especially when male. (Later [[panderer]].)
# An offer of illicit [[sex]] with a third party.
# An illicit or illegal [[offer]], usually to [[tempt]].

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# To offer [[illicit]] sex with a third party; to [[pimp]].
# To [[tempt]], usually by [[appeal]]ing to [[improper]] [[motivator]]s such as [[religious]] [[bias]] or [[racist]] opinions.

